{{BLP sources|date=September 2009}}
'''Robert Waller''' (born September 1955) is a British election expert, author, teacher, and former opinion pollster. His best known published work is ''[[The Almanac of British Politics]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2002/aug/01/politicalbooks.books|title=Redrawing the map|last=Glover|first=Julian|date=1 August 2002|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=5 June 2011}}</ref> (8 editions, 1983–2007), a guide to the voting patterns of all [[Parliamentary constituencies of the UK parliament|United Kingdom parliamentary constituencies]].

==Education and career==

Waller was born in [[Stoke-on-Trent]], and educated first at [[Buxton College]] in Derbyshire, and then at the [[University of Oxford]]. In 1977, he earned a BA in History from [[Balliol College, Oxford|Balliol College]],<ref>The Balliol College Register 7th edition; Balliol College 2005.</ref> and in 1981, graduated from [[Merton College, Oxford|Merton College]]<ref>Merton College Register II; Merton College 1990.</ref> with an MA and [[Doctor of Philosophy|D.Phil]]. in History. His doctoral thesis, a historical study of [[the Dukeries]] district of Nottinghamshire,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Robert|first=Waller|date=|year=1981|title=The social and political development of a new coalfield|url=https://ora.ox.ac.uk/objects/uuid:cc754baf-f53c-4209-9b0c-0cf746ac6d38|journal=|language=en|publisher=Oxford Research Archive|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> was published by [[Oxford University Press]] in 1983 under the title ''The Dukeries Transformed''.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/The-Dukeries-Transformed-Development-Twentieth-century/dp/0198218966 |title=The Dukeries Transformed: The Social and Political Development of a Twentieth-century Coalfield |series=Oxford Historical Monographs |first=Robert J. |last=Waller |place=Oxford |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=1983 |ISBN=0-19-821896-6 }}</ref> He was a Fellow of [[Magdalen College, Oxford|Magdalen College]] from 1980 to 1984.<ref>Magdalen College Register, 9th issue; Magdalen College 1997.</ref>

From 1984 to 1986 Waller was a lecturer and tutor in Politics and History at the University of Oxford, as well as an assistant professor at the [[University of Notre Dame]]. In 1986, he became the research director of the [[Harris Insights & Analytics|Harris Research Centre]], responsible for national opinion polling. He remained in this position until 1998, when he took up secondary school teaching. He has since taught at [[Brighton College]], [[Dame Alice Harpur School]] in Bedford, and [[Haileybury and Imperial Service College|Haileybury]] in Hertford. In 2001 he was made head of History and Politics at the [[Greenacre School for Girls]] in Banstead, Surrey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greenacre.surrey.sch.uk/explorer/file/stuff/Staff%20List%202012-13%20Website.pdf|title=Greenacre School staff list|accessdate=9 August 2012}}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In 2017 he moved to teach at [[Dunottar School]], Reigate. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dunottarschool.com/Our-School/Staff-List|title=Staff List|accessdate= 9 September 2017 }}</ref> 

From 2008 until the [[United Kingdom general election, 2010|2010 general election]], Waller contributed a monthly column to ''[[Totally Politics]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.totalpolitics.com/opinion/838/from-the-editor.thtml |title=From the editor |first=Sarah |last=Mackinlay |date=24 November 2008 |magazine=Total Politics |accessdate=5 June 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004151922/http://www.totalpolitics.com/opinion/838/from-the-editor.thtml |archivedate=4 October 2011 |df= }}</ref>

